culations.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.58,"System":0.07,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The shift-hours validator rejects a route whose total estimated time exceeds the driver's remaining shift hours, returning the excess amount.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Failure boundary is a local validator rule (compare total time vs remaining hours and compute excess). No external infra or cross-service orchestration is required. Rejected higher levels: behavior text is only about validation arithmetic and rejection output, disqualifying System/Agentic/Workflow and not requiring Integration wiring.","test_description":"Call validator with boundary cases (equal to shift, just over by minutes, large overage, fractional hours) and assert rejection flag plus exact excess-time value/rounding behavior.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.83,"Integration":0.13,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When one address in the list fails geocoding (API returns no results), the service skips that stop and optimizes the remaining addresses, reporting which addresses were skipped.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The real failure is orchestration across local modules: geocoding client result handling + skip-list bookkeeping + optimizer input filtering/output reporting. A controlled in-process geocoder stub that returns empty results reproduces this failure mode. Rejected System: behavior specifies semantic API outcome ('returns no results'), not transport-level failures (timeouts/TLS/retries) that require real network. No LLM dependence, so not Agentic/Workflow.","test_description":"Run service with a mixed address list using an in-process fake geocoding adapter that returns no results for one address and valid coordinates for others; assert skipped-address report contains the failed address and optimized route excludes it while preserving remaining stops.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.12,"Integration":0.63,"System":0.2,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Duplicate addresses in the input list are consolidated into a single stop with combined delivery items, not visited twice.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure usually appears at handoff between dedup/consolidation and route construction (state merge + planner input). A pure unit test of dedup logic may miss pipeline wiring where duplicates still enter optimizer. INTEGRATION-BRAKE: no real OS/network/subprocess needed; no AI/ML output dependence; no multi-agentic sequence.","test_description":"Execute the in-process service pipeline with duplicate-address fixtures carrying distinct delivery items; assert exactly one stop is present for that address, items are merged correctly, and final route contains a single visit to that location.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.55,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.02}}]}
